ng messages_url optimistically. Uploads require authentication, so notes would contain CAS URLs before upload, mirroring the logged-in flow. This ensures data isn't lost and allows flushes to work upon re-login. The stripping of messages occurs after enqueueing to SQLite with a pending upload. The `messages_url` would point to a hash not yet on the server, potentially causing `show-prompt` to fail until uploadedthis is acceptable.\n\nIf enqueue is called while not logged in:\n- `enqueue_authorship_metadata_to_cas` writes to SQLite, sets `messages_url` in metadata, and strips messages if `strip_after_upload` is true\n- The note would contain URLs but empty messages\n- Flushing would be skipped until login, with data stored in SQLite\n- Upon user login, uploads would work correctly So the fix could be: always enqueue data for Default mode, regardless of login status, since enqueueing only uses local storage and doesn't require API calls. This ensures data isn't lost and lets flush_cas handle authentication checks later.\n\nThis approach avoids storing data locally for users who will never use the cloud, unless privacy or legal concerns prevent it. The intent behind the CAS upload check is to avoid orphaned queue entries for casual users on the hosted service who haven't logged in. However, this leads to data loss for users who intended to use CAS but forgot to log in.\n\nA balanced fix involves:\n\n- Always enqueue data for Default mode, even when not logged in, to prevent data loss\n- This ensures that data isn't lost and allows flush_cas to handle authentication checks later\n- Enqueueing only uses local storage and doesn't require API calls, minimizing privacy impact\n- Users can still choose to use notes mode or set a custom API URL if they prefer not to enqueue locally",
