          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "## What can go wrong (yes, it can be silent)\n\n### 1. **`prompt_storage` = default + default API + not logged in** (worst case)\n\nIn `post_commit`, CAS work is gated the same way as you described: enqueue only if `is_logged_in() || api_base_url != DEFAULT_API_BASE_URL`.\n\n```382:426:src/authorship/post_commit.rs\n        PromptStorageMode::Default => {\n            // \"default\" - attempt CAS upload, NEVER keep messages/change_history in notes\n            // Check conditions for CAS upload:\n            // - user is logged in OR using custom API URL\n            let context = ApiContext::new(None);\n            let client = ApiClient::new(context);\n            let should_enqueue_cas =\n                client.is_logged_in() || using_custom_api;\n\n            if should_enqueue_cas {\n                // ... redact, enqueue, strip ...\n            } else {\n                // Not enqueueing - strip messages and change_history (never keep in notes for \"default\")\n                if !supress_output && !config.is_quiet() {\n                    eprintln!(\n                        \"[git-ai] CAS backup skipped: not logged in and using the default API. \\\n                         Prompt text was removed from the authorship note and was not stored in git or queued for upload. \\\n                         Run `git-ai login` before committing, set a custom `api_base_url`, or use prompt_storage mode \\\"notes\\\" or \\\"local\\\".\"\n                    );\n                }\n                tracing::warn!(\n                    \"prompt_storage default: skipped CAS enqueue (not logged in, default API); stripped prompts from authorship note\"\n                );\n                strip_prompt_messages(&mut authorship_log.metadata.prompts);\n                authorship_log.metadata.change_history = None;\n            }\n        }\n```\n\nPreviously there was **no** `eprintln!` / `warn!` here: the hook still stripped prompts from the authorship note, so nothing was queued for CAS and **prompt text was not in the note**. That’s easy to mistake for “it should be on the server” when nothing was uploaded.\n\n(Local SQLite may still have prompt history from other paths; the authorship **note** is what users often think of as “published” with the commit.)\n\n### 2. **Logged in at commit, then not logged in when the daemon flushes**\n\nPayloads are written to the local `cas_sync_queue`, then the telemetry worker uploads in batches. If you’re on the default API and not logged in, `flush_cas` used to **return immediately** and only log at **`tracing::debug`**, so normal runs saw nothing. The rows stay in SQLite (so it’s not the same as the “strip everything” case), but uploads **stall** until login + `git-ai flush-cas` (or a successful flush). That was improved to a **`tracing::warn!`** with the batch size and a pointer to `git-ai login` / `git-ai flush-cas`.\n\n### 3. **Notes mode + same gate**\n\nIf CAS isn’t enqueued, **redacted prompts stay in the note**, so you don’t lose git copy; CAS just isn’t synced. Less severe, but still confusing if you expect cloud backup.\n\n### 4. **Manual `git-ai flush-cas`**\n\nThis path already printed *Skipping CAS sync: not logged in and using default API* — only the **hook/daemon** paths were quiet.\n\n---\n\n## What we changed\n\n1. **Default mode, skip enqueue**: user-visible **`eprintln!`** (unless `supress_output` or quiet config) plus **`tracing::warn!`** so installs with `RUST_LOG` also see it.\n2. **Enqueue errors** (default and notes): **`eprintln!`** + **`tracing::warn!`** instead of only debug, so DB/queue failures aren’t invisible while still stripping (default) or leaving text in notes (notes).\n3. **Daemon `flush_cas` skip**: **`tracing::warn!`** with record count and recovery hints.\n\n---\n\n## Deeper product fix (optional follow-up)\n\nIf you want to **avoid dropping prompt content** when someone uses default mode without an account, you’d need a behavior change: e.g. **always enqueue to the local CAS queue** when in default mode (notes get CAS URLs, uploads happen after `git-ai login`), or **don’t strip until an upload succeeds**. That’s a larger privacy/UX tradeoff than notifications alone.",
