        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Here’s how this repo already behaves and what to do.\n\n## Built-in behavior (no code change)\n\n`DEFAULT_API_BASE_URL` is only the **fallback** when nothing else sets the URL. Resolution order is:\n\n```572:577:src/config.rs\n    // Get API base URL from config, env var, or default\n    let api_base_url = file_cfg\n        .as_ref()\n        .and_then(|c| c.api_base_url.clone())\n        .or_else(|| env::var(\"GIT_AI_API_BASE_URL\").ok())\n        .unwrap_or_else(|| DEFAULT_API_BASE_URL.to_string());\n```\n\nSo:\n\n1. **`api_base_url` in `~/.git-ai/config.json`** wins if present.  \n2. Otherwise **`GIT_AI_API_BASE_URL`**.  \n3. Otherwise the compile-time **`DEFAULT_API_BASE_URL`**.\n\nIntegration tests confirm the env var path (`tests/config_fresh_test.rs`).\n\n### What you should do as a CLI user pointing at your Railway API\n\nPick one:\n\n- **Environment variable** (good for shells, CI, systemd, Railway *if* the process running `git-ai` is on Railway):\n\n  ```bash\n  export GIT_AI_API_BASE_URL=\"https://your-service.up.railway.app\"\n  ```\n\n  Railway: **Project → Service → Variables** → add `GIT_AI_API_BASE_URL` with your public HTTPS URL (no trailing slash issues are usually handled by callers; consistent style with existing default is fine).\n\n- **Config file**: set `\"api_base_url\": \"https://your-service.up.railway.app\"` in `~/.git-ai/config.json` so you don’t depend on shell env.\n\nYou do **not** need `DEFAULT_API_BASE_URL` in Rust to match Railway if everyone uses env or config.\n\n### Railway nuance\n\nVariables in the Railway dashboard apply to **whatever runs on Railway** (your API server). The `git-ai` binary normally runs on **developers’ machines**. So:\n\n- Set **`GIT_AI_API_BASE_URL` on each developer machine / CI**, or use **`config.json`**, unless you actually run git-ai/daemon **on Railway** too—in that case define the variable on that Railway service.\n\n### If your goal is “don’t ship our production URL in source at all”\n\nThe constant in `src/config.rs` only matters for installs that never set env or config. To avoid committing a URL entirely you’d rely on **`GIT_AI_API_BASE_URL` / config** everywhere, or add a **compile-time** default via something like `option_env!(\"...\")` in CI (not implemented today as a generic knob—would be a small Rust change).\n\n**Summary:** Yes—use **`GIT_AI_API_BASE_URL`** or **`api_base_url` in `~/.git-ai/config.json`** so you never depend on editing `DEFAULT_API_BASE_URL`; Railway Variables are for processes Railway runs (your API or any git-ai daemon you host there), not automatically for laptops running the CLI unless you distribute that separately.",
